[{"id":29875,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>chloroethene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></math>-dichloroethane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn></math>-dichloroethane","1-chloroethyne"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>1,1-dichloroethane</p><p>Ethylidene chloride is a geminal dihalide with two carbon atoms. In common name system, gem-dihalides are named&nbsp;as alkylidene halides and vic-dihalides are named as alkylene dihalides. The structure of&nbsp;ethylidene chloride is:&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>CHCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>.</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29881,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cf2ef2ef-e6f7-4458-994f-f64468764408-image.png\" style=\"width: 117px; height: 148px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/298f4b8e-2c86-4517-96c5-aeccb3ebb1e1-image.png\" style=\"width: 106px; height: 78px;\" />","Both A and B","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e0191251-a815-42ea-a1cd-a1b5213e2b1e-image.png\" style=\"width: 106px; height: 113px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8512700b-a27d-424d-aac7-79d1dc4543c0-image.png\" style=\"width: 106px; height: 113px;\" />is aromatic due to cyclic conjugation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></math>-electrons.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30046,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$1, 1-$diethyl$-2,2-$dimethylpentane","$4, 4-$dimethyl$-5, 5-$diethylpentane","$5, 5-$diethyl$-4, 4-$diemthylpentane","$3-$ethyl$-4, 4-$dimethylheptane"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gS6Pzg1DAg4Jrq4x9hOidwmzNWVoaE9b6JTJ-BDrGzk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nThe correct answer is $3-$ethyl$-4, 4-$dimethylheptane. \nHence, (D) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":29806,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Reaction (I) is of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>nd</mi></msup></math> order and reaction (II) is of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>1</mn><mi>st</mi></msup></math> order","Reactions (I) and (II) both are of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>nd</mi></msup></math> order","Reactions (I) is of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>1</mn><mi>st</mi></msup></math> order and reaction (II) is of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nd</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;order","Reaction (I) and (II) both are of 1st order"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;reactions takes place via formation of carbocation. The speed of the reaction depends on the stability of carbocation. Electron releasing groups supports the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;reactions. The&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;reactions are takes place through the formation of transition state. The transition can be stabilised by electron withdrawing groups.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eaac0e3d-4528-4d2f-8874-76a9e94b88ef.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 173px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d039ce5e-2724-4ae5-a9ba-d95cf6d07cf8.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 197px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29687,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["\\(e, g\\) aromatic and \\(a, b, c, d, f, h\\) not aromatic","\\(b, e, f, g\\) aromatic and \\(a, c, d, h\\) not aromatic","\\(a, b, c, d\\) aromatic and \\(e, f, g, h\\) not aromatic","\\(a, c, d, e, h\\) aromatic and \\(b, f, g\\) not aromatic"],"answer":3,"solution":"Aromatic compounds<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/BEzs5JjYuIzsrReKhhmQ1NZwqoReL-GgtgTXWw4AowI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />a, c, d, e, h follow Huckel's rule<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0BTB9W9YtUEuIwFnKDQDEuQrVeX4-H75VtdCLPSjero.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />\\(b, f, g\\), are not aromatic, these compounds do not follow Huckel's rule","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29776,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A-I, B-II, C-III, D-IV","A-IV, B-I, C-II, D-III","A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II","A-II, B-I, C-IV, D-III"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>logK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math>, here <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math> acid dissociation constant. More the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math> value, stronger is the acidic nature of the respective acid.</p><p>Hence, the lower <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math> value denotes a more powerful acid.  Phenols are more acidic than alcohols. Hence, ethanol has more <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math> value. Nitro group is the electron withdrawing group, hence it increases the acidic nature of phenols.  Among the given phenols para nitrophenol  is stronger acid. The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math> values are matched below.</p><p>Ethanol <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn></math></p><p>Phenol<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo><mn>10</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>-</mo></math>Nitrophenol <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>-</mo></math>Nitrophenol<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p>Hence, the answer is option D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29672,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["2-Bromo-2-methylbut-2-ene","3-Bromo-3-methylprop-2-ene","1-Bromo-2-methylbut-2-ene","4-Bromo-3-methylbut-2-ene"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/FEqKSeiW8qSfjvfZ7UAJjw6Nv-Rp9lhWe7sdrrAdmV8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />1-Bromo-2-methyl but-2-ene","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29965,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Steric interactions","Angle strain","Torsional strain","Electrostatic forces of interaction"],"answer":1,"solution":"In acyclic compound torsional, steric and Van der wall&#39;s strains are present<br /><br />In cyclic compound angle strain is found due to ring. Hence, in acyclic compounds angle strain does not govern the stability of a confirmation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29714,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["nature of compound and presence of impurity.","neither on nature of compound nor on the impurity present.","nature of compound only.","presence of impurity only."],"answer":0,"solution":"Organic compounds are purified based on their nature and impruity present in it.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30064,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["1- chloropentane","3-chloro-2- methyl pentane","1-chloro -2- methyl pentane","2- chloropentane"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0UaBwFd5I2HLfqIxcepWdQ43Ceez2C9UdEKqsMEdfSM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":29899,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The density order</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/70907ed2-a445-49b0-b0ff-ed611a8d326b-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 113px;\" /></p><p>Density is directly proportional to molecular mass.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29791,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Due to the presence of some groups, the electron density decreases on ortho and para positions. So, the electron density on meta position is relatively higher than ortho and para positions. Thus, these groups directs the electrophilic substitution on meta position.</p><p>If the atom attached to the benzene ring contains a pi bond, then the atom containing group acts as meta directing group.<br/>Meta directing groups among the given groups are:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COR</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COOH</mi></math><br/>are meta directing.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29834,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["a only","c only","Both a and c","b only"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d9da1aac-a909-4660-8809-496b6d8bc39e-9893989_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 418px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>Due to the presence of two electron-withdrawing&nbsp;carbonyl group&nbsp;the methylene protons are very much acidic. The&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;effect of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>COCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is more than&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>COOMe</mi></math>. Hence, the acidic nature of acetyl acetone is more than rest of the two molecules.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29767,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","$\\stackrel{+\\quad}{\\mathrm{C}\\mathrm{H}_3}>\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\stackrel{+ \\quad}{\\mathrm{C} \\mathrm{H}_2}>\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\underset{| \\atop \\stackrel{ \\atop }{\\huge \\mathrm{CH}_3}}{\\stackrel{+ \\quad}{\\mathrm{C} \\mathrm{H}}}>\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right) \\mathrm{C}^{+}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><mo>-</mo><mtext>Tertiary carbocation</mtext><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo><mtext>Secondary carbocation</mtext><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mtext>Primary carbocation</mtext><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mtext>Methyl carbocation</mtext></math></p><p>Stability of carbocations depends upon the electron releasing groups. The given carbocations stability can be explained by hyperconjugation effect. More the number of alpha hydrogen, more are number of hyperconjugation structures, hence, more is the stability of carbocation.</p><p>Thus, the observed order of stability for carbocations is as follows: tertiary &gt; secondary &gt; primary &gt; methyl</p><p>Hence, option C is correct.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30052,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Acidic permanganate","Acidic dichromate","Chromic anhydride in glacial acetic acid","Pyridinium chloro – chromate"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":29846,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CONH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COCl</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>CHO</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COCl</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CONH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>CN</mi></math>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fe0c7206-ef1a-4b0e-b963-717d1a7df809-image.png\" style=\"width: 284px; height: 55px;\" /></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COOR</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CONH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COCl</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In the case of polyfunctional compounds, one of the functional groups is chosen as the principal functional group and the compound is then named on that basis. The remaining functional groups, which are subordinate functional groups, are named as substituents using the appropriate prefixes. The choice of principal functional group is made on the basis of order of preference. The order of decreasing priority for some functional groups is:</p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>COOH</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8211;</mo><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COOR</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>alkyl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>group</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>COCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CONH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>CN</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>HC</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>.</mo></math><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For example, the IUPAC name of</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HOCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>COCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;7-hydroxyheptan-2-one.</p><p>The correct decreasing order of priority of given functional groups is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COCl</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CONH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>CN</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29726,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect.","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct."],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6KGYhrOBJ7PesOaeB7N622FCIaFtqOhYUbPF5rseKd4.original.fullsize.png\"><br />IUPAC name\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Rightarrow 1 \\text {-chloro-2, 4-dinitrobenzene } \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\text { statement-I is incorrect }\n\\end{aligned}$<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/U4Vcj4lr-taUgZuhjkfBr2veVXTKvKOdPNF_bZyRsTE.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\begin{aligned} & \\Rightarrow \\text { 4-ethyl-2-methylaniline } \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\text { statement-II is correct }\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29851,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Acidic nature is more, if the stability of the conjugate base is more. Electron withdrawing groups increases the stability. Nitro group at para position shows <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;effect and meta position it shows <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;effect only.</p><p>Methoxy group at meta position shows <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;effect, but effect is Iess than nitro group. Methoxy group at para position shows <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;effect that decreases the acidic nature.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8a53802b-c584-445d-832b-53702ea41d17-deb5ca98-8313-45a1-bc45-34c0311674f5-9754862.png\" style=\"width: 440px; height: 188px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29884,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Dumas method formula:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mi>CuO</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>xCO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mi>Cu</mi></math></p><p>Comparing it with the given compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>&nbsp;we get&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29779,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The structures of the compounds pyrrole, Furan, thiophene, pyridine, cysteine and tyrosine respectively are follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ed1caae5-1189-40fb-b658-4dba7f6d2a64.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 282px;\"/>Hence from the given compounds, Thiophene and Cysteine are the compounds containing Sulphur.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29775,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["C &lt; D &lt; B &lt; A","A &lt; B &lt; C &lt; D","A &lt; B &lt; D &lt; C","D &lt; C &lt; B &lt; A"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Alkynes are acidic because they can release hydrogen atoms to form alkylide ions, because the hydrogen is attached more electronegative <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sp</mi></math> hybridised carbon. After that alkenes are more acidc than alkanes due to the presence of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> carbon atom in alkenes. Among the two alkanes acidic nature order is decided by the inductive effect. Methyl groups are electron releasing groups, hence they decrease the acidic nature. Hence, the overall order is</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d81390bc-7b0d-46a0-b86c-7348b66a367d.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 131px;\"/></p><p>Stability of conjugate base <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>∝</mo></math> acidic strength</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo> </mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30057,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Heat of vaporization","Gaseous densities at the same temperature and pressure","Boiling points","Vapour pressure at the same temperature"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\because$ the molecular weight of $\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{OH} \\& \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OCH}_3$ are same so in its vapour phase at same temperature \\& pressure the densities will be same","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":29669,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A-IV, B-II, C-III, D-I","A-II, B-III, C-I, D-IV","A-III, B-IV, C-II, D-I","A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RqatzEPDrXirmgmXc1rw4uFzhHxAL19QnhSL6G9QJ18.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29918,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8a8f4784-d223-428c-8264-6974ede6a9aa-image.png\" style=\"width: 115px; height: 106px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/08a6942c-b854-4eef-9270-41ab72af30fa-image.png\" style=\"width: 86px; height: 96px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/329b4146-16df-48b5-a953-36862b4f201c-image.png\" style=\"width: 115px; height: 126px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b4c355ea-7b04-4577-a1ab-81aaecfe5533-image.png\" style=\"width: 122px; height: 87px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dd189bd6-4035-45b8-947c-20275ec51c27-image.png\" style=\"width: 355px; height: 104px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29699,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":0,"solution":"In Dumas method nitrogen present in organic compound is converted into $\\mathrm{N}_2$ gas whose volumetric analysis gives the percentage of nitrogen atom in the organic compound.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30025,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(E)-2-hepten-4-yne","(Z)-5-hepten-3-yne","(E)-5-hepten-3-yne","(Z)-2-hepten-4-yne"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xZGqZ67Bq5Py9lVPOJiTjjJ9Ll54BFsINxzDBxAi8R0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":29999,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["4","5","6","3"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Firstly we calculate DU (Degree of unsaturation) of given molecular formula as :-</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DU</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p>for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>14</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DU</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mn>14</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>&nbsp;possibility is for alkanes only.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ac165387-8201-4b26-a330-e5e488a76f7e-image.png\" style=\"width: 262px; height: 30px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fc02cd64-a5fd-41de-9961-1e4c30976247-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 82px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/54ec0f06-c2b7-439b-9c4b-6a645b087e5f-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 74px;\" /></p><p>(PCC stands for parent carbon chain)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>&nbsp;Total structural isomers of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>14</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/72a2633a-4b35-465a-84d4-64efb396e413-image.png\" style=\"width: 365px; height: 180px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29914,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Positional isomerism","Both positional isomerism and metamerism","Metamerism","Functional group isomerism"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b9198d02-aee6-4df2-97a0-37bd92c5d59b-image.png\" style=\"width: 357px; height: 107px;\" /></p><p>They are functional group isomerism.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29747,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Urea","Phenyl hydrazine","Glycene","Hydrazine"],"answer":3,"solution":"Hydrazine $\\left(\\mathrm{NH}_2-\\mathrm{NH}_2\\right)$ have no carbon so does not show Lassaigne's test.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30018,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Carbocation","Free radical","Carbanion","Carbene"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>(-) - 1 - chloro-1-phenylethane is:</p><p>&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/GDHR.JPG\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 85px;\" />.<br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/135689.png\" style=\"width: 597px; height: 105px;\" /><br /><br />With SbCl<sub>5</sub> carbocation is formed. As the carbocation is&nbsp;planar, <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>Cl</mtext> <mo>&#8854;</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> can again attack from both sides giving racemic mixture. (d, l mixture formed)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29895,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> is true but statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> is false.","Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> is false but statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> is true.","Both statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> are true.","Both statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> are false."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Explanation :- aniline is more basic than acetamide because in acetamide, lone pair of nitrogen is delocalised to more electronegative element oxygen.</p><p>In Aniline lone pair of nitrogen delocalised over benzene ring.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29721,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":1,"solution":"Nitrogen present in pyridine can not be estimated by Kjeldahl method as the nitrogen present in pyridine can not be easily converted into ammonium sulphate.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29782,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Br</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The sodium fusion test, or Lassaigne's test, is used in elemental analysis for the qualitative determination of the presence of foreign elements, namely halogens, nitrogen, and sulphur, in an organic compound.</p><p>In Lassaigne's test, if both N and S are present in the organic compound, they are converted to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaSCN</mi></math>.</p><p>If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>SCN</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math> is added to a solution with iron(III) ions, a blood-red solution forms mainly due to the formation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Fe</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>SCN</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>5</mn></msub><msup><mo>]</mo><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29675,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(B) & (D) only","(A) & (B) only","(B) & (C) only","(A) & (C) only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/oqRU_SW7CWqoGIrbCqsDBPyv5iDFJp0akuMtO71P59c.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cwJidgpjf73aRvhtfm_hxTgJ-4pHYg3QNGgsWsufJqE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29642,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$c < b < d < a$","$c < a < b < d$","$d < b < a < c$","$a < b < c < d$"],"answer":2,"solution":"The electron withdrawing power ($-I$ effect) of various functional groups follows the standard experimental order:<br><br>$-NO_2 > -CN > -COOH > -F > -Cl > -Br > -I$<br><br>Based on this series, the increasing order of electron withdrawing power for the given groups is:<br><br>$-I < -COOH < -CN < -NO_2$<br><br>This corresponds to the sequence $d < b < a < c$.<br><br>Answer: $d < b < a < c$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null}]